04635nam a22005775i 9780822384533DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223845337 a10.1515/97808223845332doi  a(DE-B1597)554185  a(OCoLC)1226679137  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aPS217.P64bG76 2003 7aLIT0040202bisacsh1 aGrossman, Jay, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReconstituting the American Renaissance :bEmerson, Whitman, and the Politics of Representation /cJay Grossman; ed. by Donald E. Pease. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b4 illus., 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Americanists : 1600tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction. Representative Strategies -- tChapter One. The Rise of the Representational Arts in the United States -- tChapter Two. Rereading Emerson/Whitman -- tChapter Three. Class Actions -- tChapter Four. Representing Men -- tNotes -- tWorks Consulted -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aChallenging the standard periodization of American literary history, Reconstituting the American Renaissance reinterprets the works of Ralph Waldo Emerson and Walt Whitman and the relationship of these two authors to each other. Jay Grossman argues that issues of political representation—involving vexed questions of who shall speak and for whom—lie at the heart of American political and literary discourse from the revolutionary era through the Civil War. By taking the mid-nineteenth-century period, traditionally understood as marking the advent of literary writing in the United States, and restoring to it the ways in which Emerson and Whitman engaged with eighteenth-century controversies, rhetorics, and languages about political representation, Grossman departs significantly from arguments that have traditionally separated American writing in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries.Reconstituting the American Renaissance describes how Emerson and Whitman came into the period of their greatest productivity with different conceptions of the functions and political efficacy of the word in the world. It challenges Emerson’s position as Whitman’s necessary precursor and offers a cultural history that emphasizes the two writers’ differences in social class, cultural experience, and political perspective. In their writings between 1830 and 1855, the book finds contrasting conceptions of the relations between the “representative man” and the constituencies to whom, and for whom, he speaks. Reconstituting the American Renaissance opens up the canonical relationship between Emerson and Whitman and multiplies the historical and discursive contexts for understanding their published and unpublished works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAmerican literaturey19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aRepresentative government and representation in literature. 0aRepresentative government and representationzUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aPease, Donald E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDuke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311071183740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822384533zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822384533423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780822384533/original  a978-3-11-071183-7  Duke University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_DUK_A